#Text=THE PAWNBROKER'S SHOP
#Text=Stuffed behind the counter , and on the shelves of the pawnbroker 's shop , were articles in almost endless variety .
#Text=All was fish that came to his net .
#Text=He was willing to advance on anything that had a marketable value , and which promised to yield him , I was about to say , a fair profit .
#Text=But a fair profit was far from satisfying the old man .
#Text=He demanded an extortionate profit from those whom ill-fortune drove to his door for relief .
#Text=Eliakim Henderson , for that was his name , was a small man , with a bald head , scattering yellow whiskers , and foxlike eyes .
#Text=Spiderlike he waited for the flies who flew of their own accord into his clutches , and took care not to let them go until he had levied a large tribute .
#Text=When Paul entered the shop , there were three customers ahead of him .
#Text=One was a young woman , whose pale face and sunken cheeks showed that she was waging an unequal conflict with disease .
#Text=She was a seamstress by occupation , and had to work fifteen hours a day to earn the little that was barely sufficient to keep body and soul together .

#Text=Confined in her close little room on the fourth floor , she scarcely dared to snatch time to look out of the window into the street beneath , lest she should not be able to complete her allotted task .
#Text=A two days ' sickness had compelled her to have recourse to Eliakim Henderson .
#Text=She had under her arm a small bundle covered with an old copy of the Sun .
#Text=“ What have you got there ? ” asked the old man , roughly .
#Text=“ Show it quick , for there 's others waiting . ”
#Text=Meekly she unfolded a small shawl , somewhat faded from long use .
#Text=“ What will you give me on that ? ” she asked , timidly .
#Text=“ It is n't worth much . ”
#Text=“ It cost five dollars . ”
#Text=“ Then you got cheated .
#Text=It never was worth half the money .
#Text=What do you want on it ? ”
#Text=The seamstress intended to ask a dollar and a half , but after this depreciation she did not venture to name so high a figure .
#Text=“ A dollar and a quarter , ” she said .
#Text=“ A dollar and a quarter ! ” repeated the old man , shrilly .
#Text=“ Take it home with you .
#Text=I do n't want it . ”
#Text=“ What will you give ? ” asked the poor girl , faintly .
#Text=“ Fifty cents .
#Text=Not a penny more . ”
#Text=“ Fifty cents ! ” she repeated , in dismay , and was about to refold it .
#Text=But the thought of her rent in arrears changed her half-formed intention .
#Text=“ I 'll take it , sir . ”
#Text=The money and ticket were handed her , and she went back to her miserable attic-room , coughing as she went .
#Text=“ Now , ma'am , ” said Eliakim .
#Text=His new customer was an Irish woman , by no means consumptive in appearance , red of face and portly of figure .
#Text=“ And what 'll ye be givin ' me for this ? ” she asked , displaying a pair of pantaloons .
#Text=“ Are they yours , ma'am ? ” asked Eliakim , with a chuckle .
#Text=“ It 's not Bridget McCarty that wears the breeches , ” said that lady .
#Text=“ It 's me husband 's , and a dacent , respectable man he is , barrin ' the drink , which turns his head .
#Text=What 'll ye give for ' em ? ”
#Text=“ Name your price , ” said Eliakim , whose principle it was to insist upon his customers making the first offer .
#Text=“ Twelve shillin 's , ” said Bridget .
#Text=“ Twelve shillings ! ” exclaimed Eliakim , holding up both hands .
#Text=“ That 's all they cost when they were new . ”
#Text=“ They cost every cint of five dollars , ” said Bridget .
#Text=“ They was made at one of the most fashionable shops in the city .
#Text=Oh , they was an illigant pair when they was new . ”
#Text=“ How many years ago was that ? ” asked the pawnbroker .
#Text=“ Only six months , and they ai n't been worn more'n a month . ”
#Text=“ I 'll give you fifty cents . ”
#Text=“ Fifty cints ! ” repeated Mrs. McCarty , turning to the other customers , as if to call their attention to an offer so out of proportion to the valuable article she held in her hand .
#Text=“ Only fifty cints for these illigant breeches !
#Text=Oh , it 's you that 's a hard man , that lives on the poor and the nady . ”
#Text=“ You need n't take it .
#Text=I should lose money on it , if you did n't redeem it . ”
#Text=“ He says he 'd lose money on it , ” said Mrs. McCarty .
#Text=“ And suppose he did , is n't he a-rollin ' in gold ? ”
#Text=“ I 'm poor , ” said Eliakim ; “ almost as poor as you , because I 'm too liberal to my customers . ”
#Text=“ Hear till him ! ” said Mrs. McCarty .
#Text=“ He says he 's liberal and only offers fifty cints for these illigant breeches . ”
#Text=“ Will you take them or leave them ? ” demanded the pawnbroker , impatiently .
#Text=“ You may give me the money , ” said Bridget ; “ and it 's I that wonder how you can slape in your bed , when you are so hard on poor folks . ”
#Text=Mrs. McCarty departed with her money , and Eliakim fixed his sharp eyes on the next customer .
#Text=It was a tall man , shabbily dressed , with a thin , melancholy-looking face , and the expression of one who had struggled with the world , and failed in the struggle .
#Text=“ How much for this ? ” he asked , pointing to the violin , and speaking in a slow , deliberate tone , as if he did not feel at home in the language .
#Text=“ What do you want for it ? ”
#Text=“ Ten dollar , ” he answered .
#Text=“ Ten dollars !
#Text=You 're crazy ! ” was the contemptuous comment of the pawnbroker .
#Text=“ He is a very good violin , ” said the man .
#Text=“ If you would like to hear him , ” and he made a movement as if to play upon it .
